{
  "texts": [
    "This is used to infer that there exists a separated net Z, for which there is no biLipschitz bijection F: Z → Z d. Existence of such bijections was previously an open question of Gromov.Later, these ideas were refined by Dymond et al [22].",
    "They study the pushforward equationπ # L d |Q = ρL d |π(Q).",
    "(1.2)Note that if π is injective, then (1.2) is the same as (1.1) by the change of variables formula.",
    "They show that there exists ρ ∈ L ∞ (Q) (once again, it may be assumed that ρ only attains two positive values) such that (1.2) admits no Lipschitz regular solutions (for the relevant definitions, see the paper [22]).",
    "This is used to assert a statement about Lipschitz maps fromn d point subsets of Z d to the regular n d square in Z d as n → ∞.Concerning the (lack of) regularity of the equation (1.1), there are multiple \"scales\" of relevant questions."
  ]
}